<DESCRIPT>  HOLIDAY; FESTIVAL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  FIREWORKS, festivals, food and fun are all a part of the long Fourth of July
weekend. Here are some highlights:;    (check) Downtown San Jose: From
Thursday to Sunday, the San Jose America Festival takes over Guadalupe River
Park with a lineup of free performances, a food fair, an arts show and a
children's festival.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MARK THE FOURTH WITH FESTIVITIES AROUND THE BAY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  SETTING THE RECORD STRAIGHT (publ. 7/4/91, pg. 2D);  Because of an editor's
error, a Wednesday Living roundup of Fourth of July events incorrectly
described plans at the Harvey West Park in Santa Cruz tonight. There will be
music, food and entertainment, starting at 11 a.m. There will be no fireworks.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The America Festival incorporates five downtown events -- Kidland, a
playground/project area for children; the Great Taste, a food and music fair;
the Multicultural Arts Showcase; Tapestry in Talent, the 16-year-old art fair;
and the Independence Day Fireworks Sky Concert.;    The fireworks will be
launched Thursday over Guadalupe River Park starting between 9:20 and 9:30
p.m. The 20-minute show is choreographed with lights and sound and has its own
score and text. Playwright and director Luis Valdez will deliver the oratory,
and the Fabulous Drifters will start the show with "America the Beautiful.";  
 The Great Taste, featuring foods from 20 downtown restaurants, will be open
in Guadalupe River Park 11 a.m. to 9 p.m. Thursday and 11 a.m. to 7 p.m.
Friday. Kidland, a playground and project area for children, will take over a
section of the park near the Children's Discovery Museum from 11 a.m. to 7
p.m. Thursday and Friday.;    Tapestry in Talent brings artists to Guadalupe
River Park and Almaden and Park boulevards from 10 a.m. to 7 p.m. Saturday and
Sunday. The entertainment portion of Tapestry in Talent takes place on four
stages both days and features lots of jazz and blues this year.;    Downtown's
newest festival, the Multicultural Arts Showcase, brings to two stages
performing groups from many of the area's ethnic communities Thursday and
Friday.;    (check) Great America: The Santa Clara amusement park will be open
Thursday from 10 a.m. to 11 p.m. Paul Revere and the Raiders perform at 4 and
8:30 p.m., and the fireworks show begins at 9:30 p.m.;    Many people head for
Great America in hopes of finding a spot outside the park to watch the
fireworks for free. Keep in mind that many businesses surrounding Great
America reserve their parking lots for their employees on Independence Day.;  
 Santa Clara City police plan to divert traffic on streets near Great America,
and the California Highway Patrol says officers will tow cars that stop along
Highway 101. (408) 988-1776.;    (check) San Jose Giants: The baseball club
features fireworks after the game tonight and Thursday night. The games start
at 7:15 p.m. at Municipal Stadium, Tenth and Alma streets, San Jose. Admission
is $5, $3 for seniors and children. (408) 297-1435.;    (check) Santa Clara's
Fourth of July Celebration: 17th annual All City Picnic. Pancake breakfast,
entertainment, swimming, games, food booths. Race registration from 7:15-8:15
a.m. Race begins at 8:30 a.m. Thursday. Ceremony to honor Santa Clara's men
and women in the military services at noon, Pavilion picnic area. (408)
984-3257.;    (check) Sunnyvale Fourth of July Celebration: Sponsored by the
City of Sunnyvale's Parks &amp; Recreation Department. Pony rides, petting zoo,
carnival games and circus skills workshops, live entertainment, food booths.
10 a.m.-5 p.m., Thursday, Washington Park, 840 W. Washington Avenue,
Sunnyvale. Free. (408) 730-7515.;    (check) Mirassou Winery: Wine-tasting
begins at 7 p.m. Thursday, followed by a pops concert with the Nova Vista
Symphony and fireworks at the winery, 3000 Aborn Road, San Jose. Tickets, $20,
are available at the Mirassou Tasting Room and at BASS/TM outlets only. (408)
274-4000.;    (check) De Anza College: An all-day Cupertino festival Thursday
will culminate with a jazz concert on the soccer and baseball field at De Anza
College, followed at 9 p.m. by a fireworks show.;    (check) Milpitas: Five-
and 10-kilometer runs begin at 8:30 a.m. Thursday at the city's sports
complex, 1325 E. Calaveras Blvd. Then it's fun in adjacent Cardoza Park from 9
a.m. to 4 p.m. Fireworks are launched from the Main Street fire station, 25 W.
Curtis St., at 9:30 p.m.;    (check) Palo Alto: The Chili Chase 5K run starts
at 8:30 a.m. Thursday at Mitchell Park, 600 East Meadow Drive. ($8
registration fee). At 11 a.m., the folk trio Shanachie performs Patriotic
songs; at noon, the public judges the chili. At 3:30 p.m.: the best legs
contest, volleyball and ultimate frisbee demonstration.;    (check) Mountain
View: Moffett Field holds a public celebration from 9 to 11 a.m. Thursday to
honor the U.S. military. Gates open at 8 a.m.;    The San Francisco Symphony
will play a pops concert followed by fireworks Thursday at Shoreline
Amphitheater in Mountain View. Doors open at 5 p.m. and the concert begins at
8 p.m. Tickets are $15.50-$22.50. (415) 967-4040.;    (check) Redwood City: It
all starts with a pancake breakfast at 7:30 a.m. Thursday at 814 Hamilton
Ave., downtown Redwood City. A fun run follows at 9:15 a.m., a parade begins
at 10:30 a.m. and the festival, featuring crafts, games and entertainment,
runs 1-5 p.m. Fireworks, shot over the bay from South Shore, start at 9:30
p.m. (415) 365-1825.;    (check) San Francisco: The celebration at Crissy
Field features entertainment on two stages, food concessions and fireworks.
Entertainment begins at 2 p.m. Thursday, and the evening ceremonies begin at
8:25 p.m. San Francisco Muni runs extra buses. Bus information: (415)
673-MUNI; festival information: (415) 556-0671.;    (check) Fremont's Central
Park: The fireworks show, which drew an estimated 25,000 spectators last year,
begins at 9 p.m. Thursday and will last about 30 minutes. The fireworks will
be launched over Lake Elizabeth, so any place with a view of the lake will be
a good vantage point. The city recommends Stevenson Boulevard. Unlike past
years, there will be no festivities before the fireworks. Paseo Padre Parkway
at Stevenson Boulevard.;    (check) Alameda County Fair: Pat Boone performs
Thursday at 6 and 8 p.m. in the amphitheater and fireworks begin about 9:15
p.m. The fair, at 4501 Pleasanton Ave., Pleasanton, is open 10 a.m. to 10 p.m.
Admission is $6, $3 for seniors, $1 for children 6 to 12 and free for children
under 6. (415) 846-2881.;    (check) Alameda Fourth of July Parade: Floats,
VIPs, horse units, cars and bands -- 174 entries in all -- will wind through
the city of Alameda Thursday in a celebration of this year's theme: "Blessings
of Liberty." The parade begins at 10 a.m. at Lincoln Avenue and Park Street
and concludes 3.8 miles later at Webster Street and Haight Avenue. Entrants
will perform at the Webster/Haight reviewing stand and bleachers.;    (check)
Santa Cruz: At Harvey West Park, there'll be a free public celebation starting
at 11 a.m. Thursday with music, swimming, barbecue, and entertainment.
Fireworks will take place around 9:30 p.m.;    (check) Independence Day
Celebration at Wilder Ranch: Sponsored by Monterey Bay Natural-Historical
Association and the State Parks. Fashion show of 19th-century styles,
children's parade, old-fashioned games and races. 10 a.m. to 4 p.m., Thursday,
Wilder Ranch State Park, two miles north of Santa Cruz on Highway 1. Free.
(408) 426-0505.;    (check) Aromas: Graniterock Company of Watsonville is
sponsoring a Fourth of July concert of American pop music, featuring the Santa
Cruz County Symphony, Monterey County Symphony and the Watsonville Band, in
its A.R. Wilson Quarry in the tiny Santa Cruz County town of Aromas. The
concert, to benefit the United Way of San Benito County and participating
musical groups, will be followed by fireworks. Doors open at 4:30 p.m. at the
quarry. Tickets are $20, $10 for children 3-12 and free for children under 3.
No tickets will be sold at the door. (800) 696-4515.;    (check) Concord: The
Concord Pavilion presents fireworks after shows tonight and Thursday. The
Preservation Hall Jazz Band performs tonight at 8, and the California Symphony
performs Thursday at 8 p.m. Tickets are $17 reserved and $15 for lawn seating
through BASS/TM outlets.  </TEXT>
